    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre, yet fascinating, phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are. Imagine two of those linked quantum particles; if you measure a property of one—say, its spin—you instantly know the corresponding property of the other, even if it's across the galaxy. This is not like having two matching socks in separate boxes; it's much weirder, as the particles don't have a definite state until the very moment one is measured. It's a spooky connection, as Einstein famously called it, and it's a concept that makes even the most seasoned physicist scratch their head.",
      "source": "target",
