    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but why is it considered \"spooky\" though? like, if it's just a correlation, why does it break our normal understanding of how things work?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"spooky\" part, as you put it, is because this connection seems to happen faster than the speed of light, which is a cornerstone of our normal, classical understanding of the universe. In classical physics, if two things are correlated—like knowing one coin landed heads means the other *must* be tails—that correlation is pre-determined. In the quantum world, the particles *don't* have a definite state until the measurement happens. It's as if the act of looking at one particle instantly forces the other particle, miles away, to snap into its corresponding state. This instantaneous linkage defies our everyday intuition about locality.",
      "source": "target",
