    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if there's no physical signal traveling between them, how does the second particle \"know\" what the first one did? it feels like there must be some hidden mechanism or something happening behind the scenes that we just can't see yet.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's the million-dollar question, and it's what drives so much of modern physics! The idea of a \"hidden mechanism\"—like some tiny, unseen signal zipping between them—is what Einstein and others hoped for, but experiments have strongly suggested that no such local hidden variable exists. The particles aren't secretly communicating like two tiny, fast-talking messengers; they are fundamentally linked as a single quantum system. It's less like two separate entities talking and more like they are two parts of one single, spread-out entity. This is where the true weirdness lies, and it's far stranger than a simple hidden instruction manual.",
      "source": "target",
